  { q: "What is partial-unit registration in Toronto?", a: "Partial-unit registration is a type of short-term rental license where you rent out part of your home (like a spare bedroom) while you remain living in the property. Unlike entire-unit registration which has a 180-night annual cap, partial-unit registration has no night limit whatsoever. You can legally rent 365 nights per year." },
  { q: "Do I have to be home during every guest stay?", a: "Yes, that's the core requirement. For partial-unit rentals, either you or a member of your household must be present in the dwelling during the guest's stay. You don't need to be there 24/7, but you can't leave town while guests are there. If you can't be home, a spouse, partner, or adult child living with you can fulfill this requirement." },
  { q: "Can I switch from entire-unit to partial-unit registration?", a: "You can, but it requires applying for a new registration. Toronto locks you into one type per registration period. So if you registered as entire-unit and realize partial-unit would work better, you'll need to go through the registration process again. Plan carefully before you commit." },
  { q: "What counts as 'part of a dwelling unit' for partial-unit rentals?", a: "Any portion of your home where guests don't have exclusive access to the entire property. Renting a spare bedroom, a basement room, or even multiple rooms all qualify, as long as you're also living there. The key distinction is that guests share the dwelling with you rather than having it to themselves." },
  { q: "Can I rent multiple rooms to different guests with partial-unit registration?", a: "Yes, absolutely. You can rent out several spare rooms simultaneously to different guests. As long as you remain on-site and guests are only occupying part of your home (not the entire dwelling), it qualifies as partial-unit. Many hosts in Toronto's Annex and Parkdale neighborhoods do exactly this." },
  { q: "Is the 8.5% MAT tax required for partial-unit rentals?", a: "Yes, the Municipal Accommodation Tax applies to all short-term rentals under 28 days, regardless of whether you're registered as entire-unit or partial-unit. Airbnb and VRBO collect and remit this automatically, so you don't need to handle it manually." },
  { q: "What happens if I advertise my partial-unit as an entire-unit rental?", a: "That's a bylaw violation. Toronto Municipal Code specifically states that operators with partial-unit registration cannot advertise or rent their property as an entire-unit rental. Violations can result in fines up to $100,000 and registration revocation." },
  { q: "Do I still need to prove principal residence for partial-unit registration?", a: "Yes, the principal residence requirement applies to both entire-unit and partial-unit registrations. You must provide government-issued ID and additional documents proving the STR property is where you actually live. The city may request utility bills, tax returns, or other proof." },
